VALUES
(43, 8, 37, 40, 13, 15, 15, 'my word hath no place in you', 'Connection of Spiritual Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness and rejection of truth. Both passages emphasize the lack of understanding and receptiveness to God''s message, as seen in ''my word hath no place in you'' and ''their ears are dull of hearing.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 38, 43, 5, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Father and Son', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the Father and the Son. They highlight that the Son acts based on what he sees from the Father, indicating a shared purpose and unity in action.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 38, 43, 8, 44, 44, 'ye do that which ye have seen', 'Father and Deception Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''father'' in relation to actions and truth. In John 8:38, Jesus contrasts His actions with those of the devil''s children in John 8:44, highlighting the nature of their respective ''fathers''.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 38, 43, 12, 49, 50, 'I speak that which I have seen', 'Connection of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Jesus and the Father in terms of communication. In John 8:38, Jesus speaks of what he has seen with the Father, while in John 12:49-50, he states that he speaks only what the Father commands.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 38, 43, 3, 32, 32, 'that which ye have seen', 'Connection of Testimony and Witness', 'Both passages emphasize the act of testifying based on what one has seen and heard. John 8:38 refers to speaking what is seen with the Father, while John 3:32 discusses testifying about what is seen and heard.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 38, 62, 3, 8, 10, 'ye do that which ye have seen', 'Connection of Sin and Parentage', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between one''s actions and their spiritual parentage. John 8:38 speaks of doing what one has seen from their father, while 1 John 3:8-10 contrasts the children of God and the devil based on their actions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 38, 40, 3, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of spiritual lineage and the actions of individuals based on their origins. In John 8:38, Jesus contrasts his divine origin with that of his opponents, while Matthew 3:7 highlights the Pharisees and Sadducees as a corrupt generation, suggesting a negative spiritual heritage.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 39, 48, 3, 7, 7, 'Abraham is our father', 'Children of Abraham Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''children of Abraham.'' John 8:39 suggests that true children of Abraham would act like him, while Galatians 3:7 states that those of faith are his children, linking faith to Abraham''s legacy.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 39, 43, 8, 37, 37, 'Abraham is our father', 'Connection of Abraham''s Children', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Abraham''s descendants. John 8:39 highlights that true children of Abraham would act like him, while John 8:37 acknowledges their lineage but contrasts it with their actions against Jesus.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 39, 45, 9, 7, 7, 'Abraham is our father', 'Children of Abraham Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''children'' of Abraham. John highlights that true children would act like Abraham, while Romans clarifies that not all of Abraham''s seed are considered children, focusing on Isaac''s lineage.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 39, 45, 2, 28, 29, 'Abraham is our father', 'Connection of True Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between outward identity and true spiritual lineage. John 8:39 highlights the works of Abraham, while Romans 2:28-29 focuses on inward circumcision of the heart.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 39, 40, 3, 9, 9, 'Abraham is our father', 'Connection of Abraham''s Children', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of being children of Abraham. They challenge the assumption that lineage alone guarantees a relationship with God, highlighting the necessity of actions that reflect faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 39, 40, 5, 45, 45, 'children', 'Children of Abraham and God', 'This connection highlights the concept of being ''children'' in both passages. John 8:39 emphasizes doing the works of Abraham, while Matthew 5:45 speaks of being children of the Father in heaven, suggesting a shared theme of identity and behavior linked to one''s spiritual lineage.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 39, 48, 3, 29, 29, 'Abraham is our father', 'Connection of Abraham''s Children', 'This connection highlights the concept of being Abraham''s children through actions and faith. Both passages emphasize the idea of being heirs and connected to Abraham''s legacy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 40, 43, 8, 26, 26, 'which I have heard of God', 'Connection of Truth and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of speaking truth as revealed by God. In John 8:40, Jesus speaks of the truth he has heard from God, paralleling his assertion in John 8:26 about speaking those things which he has heard from the one who sent him.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 40, 48, 4, 29, 29, 'a man that hath told you the truth', 'Persecution of the Righteous', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by those who embody truth and the Spirit. Both passages emphasize the conflict between those born of the flesh and those born of the Spirit, reflecting the opposition Jesus faced from those who sought to kill him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 40, 48, 4, 16, 16, NULL, 'Truth and Opposition', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of truth-telling leading to opposition. In John, Jesus highlights the rejection of truth by those seeking to harm him, while in Galatians, Paul questions if he has become an enemy for speaking the truth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 40, 66, 12, 12, 13, 'a man that hath told you the truth', 'Persecution of Truth Bearers', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by those who proclaim truth. In John 8:40, Jesus speaks of being sought for death despite revealing God''s truth, while Revelation 12:13 depicts the dragon''s wrath against the woman, symbolizing the persecution of those who bear witness to God''s message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 40, 19, 37, 12, 12, NULL, 'Plotting Against the Just', 'This connection highlights the theme of wickedness against the righteous. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the unjust actions of those who seek to harm the innocent, as seen in the desire to kill the truth-teller in John and the wicked plotting against the just in Psalms.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 40, 19, 37, 32, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Righteous and Wicked', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the wicked seeking to harm the righteous. In John 8:40, the speaker is targeted for speaking truth, while Psalms 37:32 describes the wicked watching the righteous with intent to slay.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 40, 43, 8, 37, 38, 'which I have heard of God', 'Connection of Truth and Abraham', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Jesus and Abraham, highlighting the contrast between Abraham''s faithfulness and the audience''s rejection of truth. The mention of seeking to kill Jesus in both verses underscores the conflict between Jesus'' message and the actions of those who claim Abraham as their father.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 41, 23, 64, 8, 8, 'we have one Father, even God', 'Fatherhood and Creation Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of God as Father. In John 8:41, the claim of having God as Father connects to Isaiah 64:8, where God is depicted as the potter, shaping His creation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 41, 23, 63, 16, 16, NULL, 'Fatherhood of God', 'Both passages emphasize God as a father figure. In John 8:41, the claim of having God as a father is made, while Isaiah 63:16 explicitly acknowledges God as our father and redeemer.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 41, 43, 8, 38, 38, NULL, 'Father and Deeds Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''father'' and the deeds associated with him. In John 8:38, Jesus contrasts what he has seen with his Father to what the others have seen with their father, which is echoed in John 8:41 where they assert their lineage from God as their Father.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 41, 43, 8, 44, 44, 'father', 'Fatherhood and Deeds', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''father'' in relation to actions. In John 8:41, the claim of having God as their father contrasts with the assertion in John 8:44 that their true father is the devil, highlighting a conflict in spiritual lineage and moral behavior.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 41, 39, 2, 11, 11, 'We be not born of fornication', 'Connection of Spiritual Parentage', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of lineage and fidelity to God. In John 8:41, the claim of being ''not born of fornication'' suggests a concern for spiritual legitimacy, while Malachi 2:11 addresses the treachery of Judah in marrying ''the daughter of a strange god,'' indicating a breach of covenantal faithfulness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 41, 2, 4, 22, 22, 'one Father, even God', 'Fatherhood of God', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of God as a father. In John 8:41, the claim of having God as Father connects to Exodus 4:22, where Israel is described as God''s son. This connection highlights the familial relationship between God and His people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 41, 5, 14, 1, 1, 'We be not born of fornication', 'Children of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of God''s children. John 8:41 refers to the spiritual lineage of believers, while Deuteronomy 14:1 affirms the status of the Israelites as children of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 42, 43, 12, 49, 49, 'neither came I of myself, but he sent me', 'Connection of Divine Sending', 'Both passages emphasize that Jesus was sent by the Father and did not act on his own authority. This connection highlights the relationship between Jesus and God as one of divine mission and obedience.', 'theme', 0.986, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 42, 43, 14, 10, 10, 'neither came I of myself', 'Connection of Divine Origin', 'Both passages emphasize that Jesus'' words and actions are not of himself but come from God. This connection highlights the unity between Jesus and the Father, indicating that Jesus is sent by God and embodies His will.', 'theme', 0.9159999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
